/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:141:This is an *inequality* (not equality), analogous to the local energy inequality for the full solution, but restricted to the level-set region {|u| > C_k}. The last two terms are the **pressure localization terms** — Vasseur must control div(uP) and the remaining pressure term.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:151:The factors 2^{6k} and 2^{3k} arise from Δη_k and ∇η_k respectively — these are the "cutoff localization costs."
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:189:| Pressure localization | Must bound P at each scale r, requires P ∈ L^{3/2}(Q_r) | Compactness absorbs pressure implicitly | P_k = P_k^1 (harmonic) + P_k^2 (local); controlled by global ||P||_{L^p(L¹)} |
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:264:Vasseur shows (Appendix, Conjecture 14): **if** Proposition 3 held with β_p > 3/2, then ALL suitable weak solutions would be globally bounded (full regularity). The proof rescales u_ε(t,x) = ελu(t₀+λ²t, x₀+λx); the rescaled initial energy U_{ε,0} ~ ε^{2−5/λ}·(global energy)·λ → 0 as λ → 0 when 2β − 3 > 0 ↔ β > 3/2. So the threshold β = 3/2 is **precisely the boundary between partial and full regularity** in the De Giorgi framework. The current proof achieves β = 4/3 (limited by local pressure), which falls short.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:282:CKN's localization generates cutoff error terms like:
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:288:**Vasseur avoids this ε-absorption entirely** for the level-set energy estimates, replacing it with the De Giorgi mechanism (Lemma 12 + superlinear recursion). However, the pressure localization still requires Calderón-Zygmund estimates with **fixed L^q constants** (not optimal, but existential), which is where the 4/3 exponent arises.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:309:**Conclusion:** De Giorgi produces tighter estimates for the velocity/transport terms (5/3 vs 3/2), but the pressure localization in Vasseur's approach produces a new obstruction at exponent 4/3. The proof is less lossy on the nonlinear terms but encounters a new pressure bottleneck. Both proofs reach the same conclusion (partial regularity, H¹(S) = 0) but via different "weakest links."
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:5:This chain is attacking the right high-upside question, but it is structurally at risk of confusing an algebraic rewrite with a usable estimate. The central analogy to SQG is weaker than the chain admits: in SQG, the first-order commutator is tied to scalar transport and a linear constitutive law, while in NS the Lamb-vector / vorticity / Helmholtz forms are mostly equivalent repackagings of the same quadratic vector interaction. Unless the chain screens candidates at the level of the actual localized or truncated estimate that matters, it can spend several steps rediscovering textbook identities and then either overclaim a negative result or drift into Chain 03's Beltrami geometry.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:13:- The hidden assumption is that a side-by-side comparison across velocity, vorticity, Lamb-vector, and Helmholtz-projected forms can reveal a genuinely new "slot" for SQG-style cancellation. That is not obvious. These are equivalent formulations before truncation/localization, and the mission-context obstruction is precisely that the bad behavior appears after truncation/localization.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:15:- The kill condition is badly calibrated. "No candidate identity survives truncation or localization even formally" is too weak a screen. Many identities survive formally and still fail exactly where the proof needs them. A formal survival test will let dead candidates through.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:24:- The example identity `u . grad u = grad(|u|^2 / 2) - u x omega` is textbook. After projection, the gradient is removed and one is left with the Lamb-vector term. That does not by itself reduce derivative count or remove quadraticity; it just relocates them.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:25:- Helmholtz projection is order zero. It can expose cancellations, but it does not automatically transform a second-order CZ-type obstruction into a first-order gain. The step is written as though the right rewrite might make the problem "gain-bearing" by algebra alone. That is the main hidden assumption, and it is weak.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:27:- Scale counting is not enough. A symbol can look first-order under naive counting and still fail once the relevant truncation, commutator, or nonlocal pressure reconstruction is applied. This step needs estimate-level testing, not just identity-level algebra.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:50:- The negative endpoint is too broad relative to the search procedure. "NS has no SQG-type first-order cancellation in any natural formulation tested here" is fair. Stronger language such as "no SQG-style commutator analogue survives the NS vector geometry" is not earned by checking a short list of familiar formulations.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-02.md:84:The chain is visibly captivated by the SQG analogy. That is useful as a generator of questions, but it can also force NS into a mold that the mission context already says is structurally mismatched: scalar truncation, linear constitutive law, and first-order commutator structure. A fairer framing would be "does NS possess an alternative cancellation mechanism that plays an analogous strategic role?" not "can we find the NS version of the SQG commutator?"
