/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:258:1. u ∈ L²_t H¹_x (global) + local energy inequality → E(r) controlled
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:301:This is equivalent to E(r) ≥ ε₀ · r^{s-1}. Since s − 1 < 0, this would say E(r) → ∞ as r → 0 for singular points, i.e., the scale-invariant dissipation diverges at singular points. This is plausible — in fact, for Type I blow-ups, one can prove E(r) → ∞ — but in the full generality of suitable weak solutions, E(r) ≥ ε₀ (constant) is the best the ε-regularity criterion can state.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:413:| Y1 | Pressure term in local energy inequality | 3/2 and 3 | No (ε = 1) | Separate pressure and velocity |
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:418:The key observation: **Y2 is the most significant lossy step.** The Ladyzhenskaya inequality with free parameter δ is where the proof is intentionally lossy — the power 3/2 of ||∇u||_{L²} in the vortex-stretching-type term forces a Young's inequality that introduces ν⁻³ or equivalent factors. In the *local* setting of CKN, the dissipation is sufficient to close (because the local energy inequality gives a uniform estimate), but the lossiness here is what prevents explicit computation of ε₀.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:427:1. Define suitable weak solutions (u,p) satisfying NS + local energy inequality (LEI)
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:477:which would require E(r, z₀) ≥ ε₀ · r^{s-1} → ∞ as r → 0 for singular points. This cannot be guaranteed by the structure of the local energy inequality alone — it would require knowing that the dissipation concentrates even more strongly at singular points. Whether Type I singular points (where |u(x,t)| ≤ C/√(T*-t)) satisfy such enhanced concentration is a deep open question.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:481:(b) Additional geometric/analytic information about NS singular points beyond what the local energy inequality provides.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:507:**On the local energy inequality:** CKN Definition 2.2 and the discussion in §2. This inequality was first used by Scheffer (1976); CKN strengthened the partial regularity result by proving P¹(Σ) = 0 (Scheffer had only proven the time-Lebesgue measure of the singular set is zero).
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:517:**On Robinson-Rodrigo-Sadowski (2016):** Their Chapter 13 presents the CKN proof in full, including the explicit form of the local energy inequality and the parabolic Sobolev embedding. Their §13.3 has the most explicit treatment of the pressure decomposition.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:519:**On ε₀ computability:** As noted in the Atlas NS library (atlas/execution/agents/library/factual/navier-stokes, entry R4 in exploration-001), ε₀ has never been explicitly computed. Lin (1998)'s proof is non-constructive (compactness), so it does not improve this. Vasseur (2007)'s De Giorgi approach also does not yield an explicit ε₀.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:521:**Verification note:** The precise form of (LEI-φ) — specifically the coefficient 2 in front of |∇u|² — appears in CKN (2.1). Some textbooks write the NS local energy inequality without the factor of 2 and with a different normalization of viscosity ν. With ν = 1 (CKN normalization), the factor is 2 (from 2ν = 2·1). Care is needed when comparing with papers that use ν explicitly.
