/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:301:This is equivalent to E(r) ≥ ε₀ · r^{s-1}. Since s − 1 < 0, this would say E(r) → ∞ as r → 0 for singular points, i.e., the scale-invariant dissipation diverges at singular points. This is plausible — in fact, for Type I blow-ups, one can prove E(r) → ∞ — but in the full generality of suitable weak solutions, E(r) ≥ ε₀ (constant) is the best the ε-regularity criterion can state.
